<blockquote>
<p>Could you elaborate on this? We’re using Limelight MegaPose2 to add vision measurements, so I’m wondering how that impacts Pathfinder’s Pathfind to Pose?</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>There’s two Pose’s being averaged together, one from Dead-Reckoning, and the other from Vision. Adding the Vision Pose into the average corrects the Dead-Reckoning Pose which drifts over time. PathPlanner can run a path without vision. It can work just fine with the robots Dead-Reckoning Odometry.</p>
<p>If your drivetrains dead-reckoning Pose isn’t correct. That’s a problem.<br>
If your visions Pose isn’t correct. That’s probably a bigger problem.</p>
<p>Take it a step at a time. Comment out the line for adding vision measurements. Make sure the drivetrains dead reckoning is accurate. Make a path that drives the robot forward a meter, waits a second, and then back a meter. Make sure it hits the same marks ever time. This should be really close, like a few inches.</p>
<p>Add back in your vision, make sure that in the limelight webGUI the Pose it’s reporting is correct.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2025-02-04T00:58:12.757Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":108,"readers_count":107,"score":26.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":484242,"topic_slug":"pathplanner-pathfind-to-pose-problem","display_username":"James Barnes","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":71854,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/pathplanner-pathfind-to-pose-problem/484242/10","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3504008,"name":"","username":"jacob_mazelin","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jacob_mazelin/{size}/213574_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-06T16:02:24.307Z","cooked":"<p>We found our issue with the incorrect yaw. When we were on the blue alliance, the robot’s yaw was correct, but when we switched to red, the yaw was off by 180 degrees. I’m not sure if there’s a better way to fix this, but we created an if statement so that if we’re on the red alliance, add 180 to the yaw periodically, and that did the trick. Is there a more efficient way to solve this problem?</p>
